  <div class="stage-intro">
    <h2>About this stage</h2>
    <p><strong>This is where HomeTest primarily lives.</strong> SHAPE, ASSURE and CONTRACT are largely product-agnostic (with product-specific parameters). FULFIL is the stage where the product looks and feels what it is.</p>
    <p><strong>HomeTest FULFIL:</strong> Kit ordering, sample logistics, lab processing, result return, clinical safety net, patient notifications via NHS Notify. The fulfilment shape varies by configuration (patient-initiated, clinician-initiated, GP-initiated) but the stage itself is what makes HomeTest visible as a service.</p>
    <p>Supplier switching and operational transition mechanisms live here. When a supplier exits, FULFIL manages the patient-facing transition to maintain continuity of care.</p>
  </div>

  <h2 class="section-title">Current Status</h2>

  <div class="status-section progress-section">
    <div class="status-heading heading-progress">
      <span class="status-dot dot-progress"></span>
      In Progress
      <span class="status-count">5 items</span>
    </div>
    <ul class="status-list progress">
      <li>Supply chain architecture: Notify capability assessment completed 29 April. Notify can do digital communications (SMS, email, NHS App, letters via Royal Mail) but has no infrastructure for physical kit fulfilment, lab linkage or end-to-end logistics. Notify would have to build fulfilment from scratch. Strawman drafted 30 April for Notify to mark up. Likely direction forming: Notify in for comms, parked for fulfilment and labs. All-inclusive supplier model remains working default for kit fulfilment</li>
      <li>Efficio Consulting engaged as external supply chain advisory (20 Apr). Working group established across commercial, clinical, and programme leads</li>
      <li>NHS Notify integration for patient notifications: digital comms settled as Notify's domain. Notify works through dedicated Royal Mail Health function (NHS-facing, ~18 months old). Covers large-letter postal tariffs and volume discounts</li>
      <li>Plymouth/Devon as potential NHS pathology partner. Royal Devon has acute self-sample pathways, high-sensitivity PSA analysers, NIHR centre. To be treated as external pathology provider, API in / API out. Draft EOI to partner as clinical partner, not commercial supplier</li>
      <li>HIV Beta scope: Private Beta live (up to 100 targeted tests across Salford LA with SH:24 and East Sussex CC with Preventx). Public Beta up to 1,000+, December 2026 to March 2027 window. GDS Alpha Assessment completed 30 April</li>
      <li>HPV Self-Testing architecture as comparator. Prime contractor + 8 regional NHS labs model. 4 million invitations planned year 1, 18% uptake baseline. Procurement failed twice including one legal challenge. Lessons directly applicable to framework design</li>
      <li>Four pathology supplier phenotypes identified: NHS-supplied pathology (14 networks), NHS commercial partnerships (51/49 JVs), NHS trusts with commercial offering (Royal Devon), commercial suppliers (~8 HIV-active, 15+ via transdermal RFI)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="status-section open-section">
    <div class="status-heading heading-open">
      <span class="status-dot dot-open"></span>
      Open Decisions
      <span class="status-count">7 items</span>
    </div>
    <ul class="status-list open">
      <li>Service standards and SLAs not yet defined</li>
      <li>Supplier switching process and patient continuity during transitions</li>
      
      
      <li>Cold chain logistics for temperature-sensitive tests (e.g. capillary blood for PSA)</li>
      <li>Royal Mail engagement live. Two threads in flight: (1) reliability of the Tracked 24 service for kit logistics, (2) potential new 'Health Samples' package category sized to fit new blood collection devices that currently fall outside Large Letter format and require Small Parcel format at up to three times the price. Notify works through Royal Mail Health; this engagement also runs via MarketReach; route alignment between the three paths still to be reconciled. Deep dive on Royal Mail completed; latest position carried on the Status page</li>
      <li>Whether centralised kit procurement (NHS taking on stock holding and management) is viable or contradicts the platform-orchestrates-doesn't-operate principle. Notify flagged this dependency explicitly in the 29 April session</li>
    </ul>
  </div>


